ary links among health, morality, citizenship, and identity that can be read on these pages. While women and body image are often studied together, Body Panic considers both women's and men's bodies side-by-side and over time in order to offer a more in-depth understanding of this pervasive cultural trend.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAdvertising, MagazinezUnited States. 0aBody imagezUnited States. 0aCulture. 0aExercisexPsychological aspects. 0aGender identityzUnited States. 0aPhysical fitnesszUnited StatesvPeriodicals. 4aConsiders. 4aDworkin. 4aFaye. 4aLinda. 4aShari. 4aWachs. 4abodies. 4abody. 4aboth. 4acome. 4acultural. 4afit. 4ain-depth. 4amens. 4amore. 4aoffer. 4aorder. 4aover. 4aparticular. 4apervasive. 4aside-by-side. 4athis. 4atime. 4atrend. 4atypes. 4aunderstanding. 4awomens. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aWachs, Faye Linda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785256.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK